WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:01.700
&gt;&gt; Marisa Bellack: Hello.

00:00:01.700 --> 00:00:03.000
I'm Marisa Bellack.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:05.220
I'm an editor at "The Washington
Post," a charter sponsor

00:00:05.220 --> 00:00:07.810
of the Library of Congress
National Book Festival.

00:00:07.810 --> 00:00:12.020
I'm pleased to introduce Ellen
Hopkins, bestselling author

00:00:12.020 --> 00:00:15.570
of 14 young adult novels
and four adult novels.

00:00:15.570 --> 00:00:17.220
Ellen fields a lot of
questions about how

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:20.160
to become a successful
fiction writer but her path

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:21.960
to success wasn't
necessarily typical.

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:26.270
Although she published her first
poem in a newspaper at age 9,

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:29.170
in 1964, she didn't start
writing for a living

00:00:29.170 --> 00:00:32.360
until her mid 30s and she
didn't publish her first novel

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.020
until age 49, in 2004.

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:37.120
Along the way, she ran
a catering service,

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:39.820
owned a video store,
showed horses,

00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:42.380
freelanced for newspapers
and magazines,

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:45.770
and wrote 20 nonfiction
books for children.

00:00:45.770 --> 00:00:48.490
You may have noticed
that gritty novels

00:00:48.490 --> 00:00:50.990
about difficult subjects
have become a thing

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:54.510
in the world of young
adult books.

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:57.140
But they were relatively
uncommon when Ellen got going

00:00:57.140 --> 00:00:59.910
and that's not what
she set out to write.

00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:02.470
As you may well know, her
first explosive novel,

00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:04.100
"Crank" was loosely based

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:06.860
on her daughter's
experience with crystal meth.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:09.110
Ellen chose to tell the story

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:10.980
from a fictional
daughter's perspective

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:13.760
to better understand her
real daughter's decisions

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:16.000
and to examine the role
she played as a mother.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.750
She began the novel in
prose but switched to verse

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:20.930
because she has said
in interviews,

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:22.770
"Poetry is so interior.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:27.060
It was the right way of getting
into Kristina/Bree's skin.

00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:30.020
Since then, Ellen has written
on topics ranging from abuse

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:32.770
to suicide to AIDS
to teen pregnancy.

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:35.730
Her newest book "People Kill
People," officially out Tuesday

00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:38.830
and we think there may be
some copies here today,

00:01:38.830 --> 00:01:41.710
delves into school
violence, white supremacy

00:01:41.710 --> 00:01:43.490
and other timely issues.

00:01:43.490 --> 00:01:46.760
I imagine she'll say
more about that today.

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:48.710
Before we dive into our
discussion, I'm supposed

00:01:48.710 --> 00:01:50.010
to mention that the Library

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:51.520
of Congress has been
the Festival host

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:54.330
since it began 18 years ago.

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:57.350
I want to thank festival
Co-Chairman David Rubenstein

00:01:57.350 --> 00:02:00.760
and the many sponsors who
made this event possible.

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:03.030
You can support the
festival with a donation.

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:04.950
There's information
in your program.

00:02:04.950 --> 00:02:07.160
Please note, too, that there
will be time for questions

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:09.000
after Ellen's remarks and anyone

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:10.600
who asks a question
will be filmed

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:12.570
for the Library's archives.

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:14.310
And for those who are
interested, Ellen is scheduled

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:17.590
for a book signing session from
4:00 to 5:00 this afternoon.

00:02:17.590 --> 00:02:19.510
Now please help me
welcome Ellen Hopkins.

00:02:19.510 --> 00:02:26.120
[ Applause ]

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:29.970
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: And please
help me thank the not fake news.

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:36.130
[ Applause ]

00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:39.260
Okay, how many of you
guys follow me online?

00:02:40.530 --> 00:02:44.780
Really? You guys are
scared of me, aren't you?

00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:49.330
I don't blame you because
I am a political beast.

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:52.900
So I first of all before I
talk about me or my books,

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:58.870
I really want to tell you how
grateful I am to be in DC today.

00:02:58.870 --> 00:03:03.660
This, you know, this place,
like I live in Nevada.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:08.230
I live in Northern Nevada,
not Las Vegas, okay.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:13.990
There's a whole different --
And yes, it snows in Nevada.

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:17.120
So when you're back there, you
know, we tend to look at DC

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:21.730
as like this monstrosity.

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:27.560
It's so, at least now, I
mean our political space is

00:03:27.560 --> 00:03:32.060
so contentious and it's like and
-- I think we need to really,

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:35.350
really find ways to come back
together as much as we can.

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:38.400
I hope our books will
start to do that again.

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:40.730
But I was in the hotel
room this morning

00:03:40.730 --> 00:03:42.850
when Mr. McCain's funeral was on

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:45.010
and I couldn't tear myself
away from it, you know.

00:03:45.010 --> 00:03:49.240
It was like to watch people from
both sides of the aisle be able

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.810
to come into this space
and to honor a man

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.110
who was able to do that.

00:03:54.110 --> 00:03:59.150
For me, I really feel honored
to be here today to have shared

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:00.450
in that space somehow.

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.580
I don't know, I know that's
kind of weird and kind

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:06.380
of a weird thing to talk about
but I really wanted to say that.

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:11.510
And so I do write
-- I write books.

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:14.050
You know, there's
this new article

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:15.350
in "The Wall Street Journal,"

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:18.990
you guys seen it,
The darkness of YA.

00:04:21.030 --> 00:04:23.370
Well, you know, being a teen is

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.640
like not the easiest
thing to be.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.830
You know, I mean seriously.

00:04:27.830 --> 00:04:31.630
My childhood, my teenage
years, they weren't that easy

00:04:31.630 --> 00:04:35.730
but teens today, the things
they're experiencing are harder.

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:40.240
I didn't worry about guns
coming into my school.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:43.170
That was not a concern
at all, you know.

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:45.850
Now we're teaching
elementary kids how to zigzag

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:49.140
down the hallways, you
know, and it's like, okay,

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:51.570
we need to change things.

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:54.600
And I think books are a way
to be able to bring people

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:56.830
to open eyes to problems

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:58.130
that our kids are
experiencing every single day.

00:04:58.130 --> 00:05:02.660
So I hope the parents out
there will read my books

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:07.800
with their young people and
open up lines of dialogue

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:10.410
and discussion because
that's how we are going

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.770
to change things and make
things better for our kids.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:15.700
And don't be afraid of books.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:20.610
Books are a safe, safe
space to explore addiction,

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:26.410
to explore abuse, to
explore gun violence,

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:28.390
which is what I'm here with,

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:30.660
"People Kill People,"
brand new book.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:33.390
I wanted to explore gun
violence because it's something

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:35.060
that our kids are
experiencing every day,

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:37.040
a fear of this in their lives.

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:41.510
And so we need to figure
out why this is happening,

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:46.980
who it's happening to and
who the perpetrators are

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.030
so that we can hopefully
turn this around.

00:05:50.030 --> 00:05:52.550
I'm going to read a little
bit for you and I'm going

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:54.280
to read my author note
because I want you

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:57.950
to know why I chose to do this.

00:05:57.950 --> 00:06:00.130
This is the author's note.

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:02.310
I grew up with guns.

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:03.850
My dad who was both a hunter

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:07.180
and an avid collector taught
me to respect firearms.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.240
I am, in fact, an excellent
shot and at another time

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:12.000
in my life enjoyed
target shooting.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.360
I could even do black
powder rifles.

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:16.660
Have you ever tried those?

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:18.960
They're like weird.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:22.190
Today, however, I
don't own a gun

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:23.850
and as an animal
lover would only hunt

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:25.640
if it was that or go hungry.

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.150
I respect the Second Amendment

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:29.200
but we must address the
gun violence problem

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:30.500
in the United States.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:33.480
Statistics show a steep
rise in gun-related deaths

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:35.890
and injuries since 2014.

00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:40.420
In 2017, as of November 6th,
more than 13,000 people had died

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:43.200
as a result of non-suicide
gun violence

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:47.410
with an average 93 Americans
killed by guns every day.

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:48.710
The yearend total would be

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:53.020
around 18,000 non-suicide gun
deaths, up 4000 from 2016.

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:57.390
Suicides generally account
for 62% of gun-related deaths,

00:06:57.390 --> 00:07:00.740
which would put the total
figure at more than 47,000.

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:02.880
Mass shootings, three or
more deaths per incident,

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:05.240
also show a precipitous
upward trend.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:06.950
Young people are
often involved both

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:09.430
as victims and perpetrators.

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:12.030
While the outcome of
stricter gun control continues

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.430
to be debated, I felt
it was important to try

00:07:14.430 --> 00:07:16.570
and understand why
someone might be compelled

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:17.960
to pull the trigger.

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:19.260
This is what authors do.

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:20.560
We ask why.

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:22.570
Why are people prone
to violence?

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:24.730
Why do people seek revenge?

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:27.930
Why do people hate
or fear or despair?

00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:30.130
Why do people kill people?

00:07:30.130 --> 00:07:31.740
If we can understand the whys,

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:34.620
perhaps we can begin
to solve the problem.

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:35.920
The characters you'll meet

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.280
in these pages have powerful
life situations driving them

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:41.800
in negative directions, any
one of them in a precise moment

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:45.210
in time might decide to
pick up the gun and fire it.

00:07:45.210 --> 00:07:47.810
If they seem familiar,
it's because they are,

00:07:47.810 --> 00:07:51.170
at least in some small way,
inspired by stories that pop

00:07:51.170 --> 00:07:53.100
up in news feeds every day.

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:55.330
They are fictional but real.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:57.550
My editor made me put
a disclaimer in there.

00:07:57.550 --> 00:07:58.850
Views do reflect my own.

00:07:58.850 --> 00:08:02.970
I would hope that
you would know that.

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:08.340
So on my dad, my dad
was an amazing man.

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:11.100
He was the hardest
working person I ever met

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:14.070
and he was a weekend alcoholic.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:16.290
By that I mean he
never touched a drop

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:18.810
from church Sunday
until Friday night.

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:23.470
Friday night until church
Sunday, he was wiped out.

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:26.240
So he was a responsible
gun owner.

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:27.760
He kept his guns locked up.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:29.770
I only saw them come
out on a few occasions

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:34.150
when he went hunting or on two
occasions when he was drunk.

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:37.660
He put a loaded pistol
to my mom's head.

00:08:37.660 --> 00:08:38.960
He didn't pull the trigger.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:40.530
She was able to talk him down

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:42.770
but that was something
I witnessed as a child.

00:08:42.770 --> 00:08:47.460
So all it takes is the wrong
time, you know, the wrong second

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:50.060
for something to go all wrong.

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:55.990
I'm going to read a
little bit for you.

00:08:55.990 --> 00:09:01.750
So all 13 of my YA before
this one were written in verse

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:04.680
and they were all first person.

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:08.030
Every book I've written up until
this one I wrote first person.

00:09:08.030 --> 00:09:12.550
This book, the narrator
is omniscient

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:16.940
and the narrator is the
voice of violence as seducer.

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:18.300
The six characters you'll meet

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:21.490
in the book are all
written in second person.

00:09:21.490 --> 00:09:24.230
So I invite you onto
the page, you,

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:26.830
to become those six characters.

00:09:26.830 --> 00:09:28.830
I was going to do the
whole thing omniscient

00:09:28.830 --> 00:09:31.890
and then I kept wanting
to address the reader.

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:34.380
I kept wanting to talk to
you as these characters.

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:40.230
And so I said -- First, I had to
rewrite the first 10,000 words

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:43.290
in second person but I wanted
to address you and to invite you

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:46.030
to become these people so
you could into their heads

00:09:46.030 --> 00:09:48.990
and into their spaces and
become these characters,

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:51.420
which I want it to be an
uncomfortable experience

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:52.720
for you.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:54.110
So I don't think you're going to
be comfortable reading this book

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:55.410
and that's not what
it's here for.

00:09:55.410 --> 00:09:57.040
But we'll start in
the voice of violence.

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:03.230
You, yeah you, come
here, please.

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:06.580
I need to ask you something.

00:10:06.580 --> 00:10:09.130
Have you ever felt the
desire to hurt someone,

00:10:09.130 --> 00:10:13.520
I mean pummel them, wound
them, watch them bleed?

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:16.160
Did you? Would you?

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:17.460
Could you?

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:20.650
If I were the gambling type,
I'd put my money on yes.

00:10:20.650 --> 00:10:23.950
See, there's this thing
inside every one of you,

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:26.950
the collective human
call toward violence.

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:31.390
All it takes is one singular
moment to encourage it into play

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:35.610
and the lamb transforms,
becomes the lion.

00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:37.570
Take it one step further.

00:10:37.570 --> 00:10:41.570
Have you ever thought about
killing someone, I mean,

00:10:41.570 --> 00:10:43.490
poisoning them, bludgeoning
them,

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:47.080
grabbing a well-honed knife
and carving them to pieces?

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:49.520
Chances are you haven't,
wouldn't,

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:53.280
couldn't follow through,
contemplate.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:56.990
What's required to become
the catalyst for death?

00:10:56.990 --> 00:11:00.240
A moral compass sprung
and spinning haywire,

00:11:00.240 --> 00:11:02.740
antifreeze flowing
through your veins,

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:06.160
or perhaps nothing
more than circumstance?

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:09.680
In that instant when the
lamb unleashes its roar,

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:12.070
would you heed the
call or instead defer

00:11:12.070 --> 00:11:15.340
to the quivering
voice of reason?

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:17.530
Like dawn and dusk, existence

00:11:17.530 --> 00:11:21.160
and demise are inextricably
linked as per the grand scheme,

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:23.580
either drafted by some
all-powerful architect

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:25.600
or randomly designed.

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:28.650
Perhaps this is the
true knowledge of Eden,

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:32.220
not the mechanics of procreation
but the promise that once time

00:11:32.220 --> 00:11:33.520
on Earth is nothing more

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:36.490
than a journey toward
inevitable departure.

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:39.970
Surely the ancient ones who bore
witness to birth in the wilds

00:11:39.970 --> 00:11:43.870
and death from claw or club or
predation by creatures too small

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:47.900
for the eye to identify,
we're aware of nature's plot.

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:50.420
As their spines uncurled
and they drew upright

00:11:50.420 --> 00:11:54.260
to run discovered the value
of flint, the power of spear

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:56.710
and arrow, the lust
for blood billowed

00:11:56.710 --> 00:11:59.000
like a black-bellied cloud.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.610
Oh, to wield a weapon
mercilessly extinguish a

00:12:02.610 --> 00:12:04.680
beating heart.

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:08.080
The millennia crept forward,
dawn to dusk to dawn to dusk

00:12:08.080 --> 00:12:10.890
and humankind shed its
fur, fashioned clothes,

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:14.640
deserted its caves in
favor of villages, cities.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.090
But even as people learned to
plant, harness sunlight and rain

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:22.520
to nurture garden fields, their
passion for the hunt remained.

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:26.590
They killed in the name of
survival, protection, vengeance.

00:12:26.590 --> 00:12:29.840
They killed in response to
lust, jealousy, despair.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.680
They killed for the
thrill, the simple pleasure

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:35.760
of witnessing bloodshed.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:38.200
Think for one delicious moment
how they would've watched

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:41.460
in wide-eyed reverence the
advent of gunpowder marvel

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:43.800
at the fire [inaudible]-,
its relentless evolution

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:47.540
from crude spear-driven flame
thrower into a fierce weapon,

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:51.140
able to discharge 1000
flesh-ripping metal projectiles

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.590
in 60 lethal seconds.

00:12:53.590 --> 00:12:56.330
Ponder their amazement at
a machine with the ability

00:12:56.330 --> 00:13:00.600
to level entire villages, infant
to ancient in mere minutes.

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:02.150
They would've fallen
on their knees

00:13:02.150 --> 00:13:04.600
and lifted their
arms in worship.

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:07.300
Now you understand the
talent of a firearm

00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:09.180
but perhaps you're
unaware of the force

00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:13.250
to feeling its seductiveness.

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:15.600
You know how sometimes
you hear a whisper fall

00:13:15.600 --> 00:13:18.380
over your shoulder but then you
turn to search for the source,

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:20.420
find nothing but
landscape behind you?

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.580
So then you tell yourself
it was just a case

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:25.320
of hyperactive imagination,
convince yourself

00:13:25.320 --> 00:13:28.460
that sentiments don't
materialize out of thin air

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:30.940
but the truth, at least
as I like to tell it,

00:13:30.940 --> 00:13:32.300
is that the voices
who speak to you

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:35.970
from inside your head have taken
up permanent residence there.

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.200
Some shout warning
prodding you to take cover,

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.660
flee or brandish a weapon.

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:45.830
Others murmur haunting you
with poetry, like mine.

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:49.020
So the voice of violence
is in verse.

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:51.970
The six characters are in prose.

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:54.330
I'm trying to grow
my readers up.

00:13:54.330 --> 00:13:57.650
So if you guys go back to
my first books, you know --

00:13:57.650 --> 00:13:59.850
How many of you guys started
with me with like "Crank"

00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:01.440
or "Burned" back then?

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:04.640
So you guys know as I've moved
along, like those earlier books,

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:07.620
there's more white space
on the page, right.

00:14:07.620 --> 00:14:13.960
And I've kind of -- And there's
less stylistic verse on the page

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:16.960
and that's because I'm
wanting to grow my readers up.

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:21.080
So the early books were like
very simple to read, I think,

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:25.190
although the verse for
very linear readers,

00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:27.970
like for older readers, it's
hard to get to the verse

00:14:27.970 --> 00:14:32.540
as storytelling because we're
taught to read like this.

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:35.610
Young people, their
brains pick up knowledge

00:14:35.610 --> 00:14:37.300
in a different way now
because of computers

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:38.600
and the way computers come on

00:14:38.600 --> 00:14:40.420
and the way they use
their phones and stuff.

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:42.950
So their brains are actually
hardwired a little differently.

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:45.980
They're actually a little
more open to the idea of kind

00:14:45.980 --> 00:14:51.290
of alternative formatting
visual interest on the page.

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:56.020
So it's been a pleasure for me
to be able to bring nonreaders

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:58.270
and reluctant readers to
books through that kind

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:00.230
of more visual interest.

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:02.050
But then I also want
them to become readers.

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:04.390
So if you go all
the way through,

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:07.790
the verse becomes denser and
then you're going to start

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:10.070
to get some prose from me.

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:16.940
Like the book I'm writing
now, it's almost all prose.

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:19.210
Yes, I am writing a new book.

00:15:19.210 --> 00:15:21.970
The 2019 book, which, okay,

