00:22:38.290 --> 00:22:40.970
it's difficult content for sure.

00:22:40.970 --> 00:22:44.460
Also, "Traffick" which is so --
"Tricks" is about five kids --

00:22:44.460 --> 00:22:47.150
&gt;&gt; They don't have that either.

00:22:47.150 --> 00:22:48.450
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins:
"Tricks" is about five kids

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:50.150
from all different parts
of the country who end

00:22:50.150 --> 00:22:53.250
up on the streets of Las
Vegas turning tricks, right.

00:22:53.250 --> 00:22:55.570
"Traffick" is about
what happens to them

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:56.970
after they're pulled out.

00:22:56.970 --> 00:22:58.270
Can they go back.

00:22:58.270 --> 00:22:59.570
Can they find love?

00:22:59.570 --> 00:23:00.870
Will their parents
take them back?

00:23:00.870 --> 00:23:02.800
So it's about -- One's
about victimization

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:04.740
and the other is
about survivorship.

00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:07.350
And so there is a way
out and there is hope.

00:23:07.350 --> 00:23:08.650
And I worked with a lot

00:23:08.650 --> 00:23:12.920
of survivors helping them write
their own stories, draw pictures

00:23:12.920 --> 00:23:15.960
if they couldn't write,
and so they shared a lot

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:19.350
of really interesting stories,
many of which are reflected

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:21.530
in that book, in "Traffick."

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:22.830
&gt;&gt; Okay, great.

00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:24.260
Thank you so much.

00:23:24.260 --> 00:23:25.790
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins:
Okay, over there.

00:23:25.790 --> 00:23:30.400
&gt;&gt; Okay, so what advice would
you give someone who people

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:32.750
who are close to them
are starting to go

00:23:32.750 --> 00:23:37.840
down that same path as "Crank?"

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:40.530
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: So what's
really, really hard is

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:44.150
to watch a friend go
that way or a relative.

00:23:44.150 --> 00:23:49.830
For those people, they
have to know that you care

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:52.710
about them a lot but that
you can't enable that.

00:23:52.710 --> 00:23:54.010
And it's really,
really important

00:23:54.010 --> 00:23:55.310
that you don't enable that.

00:23:55.310 --> 00:23:56.710
So like there are family --

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:58.160
You can't give them money

00:23:58.160 --> 00:23:59.960
because the money will
go there, you know.

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:02.290
Even if they say it's
going to rent or whatever,

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:06.890
to let them know that give
them a copy of a book like that

00:24:06.890 --> 00:24:09.440
or like "Tweak" or
like, you know,

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:14.940
that really shows how far you
can fall if you choose that path

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:17.440
and it doesn't take very long.

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:21.050
You can tell their parents.

00:24:21.050 --> 00:24:22.790
I mean, if you want
to get that involved,

00:24:22.790 --> 00:24:25.620
it depends on how close
you are to their family

00:24:25.620 --> 00:24:27.440
of if the whole family
knows anyway, I mean,

00:24:27.440 --> 00:24:30.390
really sometimes it takes a
real intervention to be able

00:24:30.390 --> 00:24:34.180
to save them because once
-- So like for my daughter,

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:37.270
she started at 16,
17 years old, right.

00:24:37.270 --> 00:24:41.050
She is now 38 years old and so
it's been that long of a journey

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:42.510
for her in and out of that.

00:24:42.510 --> 00:24:46.620
Even if you get help, it
will always call to you.

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:49.390
And your life, your
dreams, they go.

00:24:49.390 --> 00:24:52.380
So talk to them about their
dreams and what they want

00:24:52.380 --> 00:24:55.450
and then see if you can talk
to them about how taking

00:24:55.450 --> 00:24:57.440
that route is going to
take that dream away.

00:24:57.440 --> 00:24:59.950
For my daughter, it was her
dream was computer animation

00:24:59.950 --> 00:25:02.750
and she was on a fast
track to a full scholarship

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:06.780
at the Art Institute of Seattle
and that's all gone to her now.

00:25:06.780 --> 00:25:08.900
She can't do it anymore.

00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:12.360
So especially that kind of
drug, I mean, it's brain damage.

00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:13.660
There are a lot of
different things

00:25:13.660 --> 00:25:16.970
that go wrong when
you go that way.

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:19.410
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:23.790
&gt;&gt; First, I would
like to say thank you

00:25:23.790 --> 00:25:28.430
because your book has helped
me help other people in, like,

00:25:28.430 --> 00:25:30.040
my community and my
neighborhood so first I want

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:31.340
to give you a thank
you, Ms. Hopkins.

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:35.100
Second, I would like to ask you
where you draw your inspiration

00:25:35.100 --> 00:25:36.560
from for all these books?

00:25:36.560 --> 00:25:39.130
Like, do they come
straight from all the things

00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:42.400
that are happening like social
media and in like the world

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:45.630
or do they come from
like personal experience

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:47.450
or like survivor stories?

00:25:47.450 --> 00:25:48.960
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: It's
a mixture of both.

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:51.710
So, I mean, a lot of
it is social media.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:54.290
You know, I was really
early to social media.

00:25:54.290 --> 00:25:56.750
When I started doing this,
when "Crank" came out,

00:25:56.750 --> 00:26:00.280
the only social medial
platform out there was My Space.

00:26:00.280 --> 00:26:03.490
That gives you an idea
how long ago it was.

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:07.320
Right? But I discovered very
quickly the value of being able

