to connect online with
my readers, one on one,

00:26:11.110 --> 00:26:12.760
like it's a private space.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:14.370
So they would come to
me and share stories.

00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:17.690
And I do, I have, I keep reader
letters and there are many,

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:21.730
many, many and some of them
are just they are devastating.

00:26:21.730 --> 00:26:24.120
Those seem to come to
me like after midnight.

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:25.420
I don't know why.

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:27.170
It's like, because
I'm tired, you know,

00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:28.470
too many glasses of wine.

00:26:28.470 --> 00:26:30.640
I'm crying for these kids.

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:33.490
But social media is one
way and I do, I get stories

00:26:33.490 --> 00:26:35.680
and people want to share
their stories with me.

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:37.530
A lot of times it is family.

00:26:37.530 --> 00:26:38.830
It's friends.

00:26:38.830 --> 00:26:40.130
It might be something
I see on the news.

00:26:40.130 --> 00:26:42.990
You know, there are lots of
ways that I gather inspiration

00:26:42.990 --> 00:26:45.460
or think about new
stories or whatever.

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:46.760
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:26:46.760 --> 00:26:48.060
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: Yep.

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:57.280
&gt;&gt; So I've been reading
your books since like 2007

00:26:57.280 --> 00:27:00.700
and I was lucky because my
dad bought like "Crank, Glass,

00:27:00.700 --> 00:27:02.680
and Impulse" all at
the same time and I was

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:05.490
like that never happens
but so, yeah.

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:09.200
But the thing is, now looking on
the shelves and seeing the books

00:27:09.200 --> 00:27:12.680
and I noticed that covers
have changed and like

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:15.710
to me it feels less
impactful because like "Crank"

00:27:15.710 --> 00:27:19.860
and "Glass," you know, were like
first covers and so now I'm just

00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:23.870
like and so like I want
to know why that happened

00:27:23.870 --> 00:27:26.280
and how you feel about it.

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:28.490
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins:
So cover design is

00:27:28.490 --> 00:27:29.880
like not up to me at all.

00:27:29.880 --> 00:27:31.750
That's a publisher decision.

00:27:31.750 --> 00:27:36.640
I had the same designer for
the first several books.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:40.340
And then my publisher was like,
let's update you, let's like,

00:27:40.340 --> 00:27:42.420
you know, try to
draw new readers

00:27:42.420 --> 00:27:45.020
in because maybe those covers
are something they've seen

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:48.030
for such a long time
that they've kind

00:27:48.030 --> 00:27:49.330
of just dismissed them.

00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:50.630
Do you know what I mean?

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:51.930
I mean, there are also
readers that will open it up

00:27:51.930 --> 00:27:53.470
and see verse and that's it.

00:27:53.470 --> 00:27:56.630
They don't -- They're not
even going to do that.

00:27:56.630 --> 00:28:00.220
So covers, although I think,
I mean, that's a cover.

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:03.870
Yeah? I mean, it tells
you exactly what it is.

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:06.250
And you know why it's like that?

00:28:06.250 --> 00:28:08.900
Because big book
stores, Barnes &amp; Noble,

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:11.010
won't let young adult
have an actual picture

00:28:11.010 --> 00:28:13.320
of a gun on a cover.

00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:16.360
So book stories, did you know
book stores actually do have

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:17.940
input into cover design?

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:19.940
If they like see a cover and
they think it's not going

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:21.460
to like look good on
their bookshelves,

00:28:21.460 --> 00:28:23.980
they will actually go back to
the publisher and say this needs

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:26.550
to change for some reason.

00:28:26.550 --> 00:28:27.850
It's interesting.

00:28:27.850 --> 00:28:30.930
But yeah, cover is not
up to me so much anymore.

00:28:30.930 --> 00:28:32.230
I can veto it.

00:28:32.230 --> 00:28:34.630
If it's something I
really hated, I could say,

00:28:34.630 --> 00:28:38.730
yeah, I don't think so.

00:28:39.750 --> 00:28:41.050
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:28:41.050 --> 00:28:42.660
&gt;&gt; I recently had a
debate with a friend

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:43.960
about like the differences

00:28:43.960 --> 00:28:46.390
between young adult
books and fiction books.

00:28:46.390 --> 00:28:48.740
And I was wondering
if in your experience,

00:28:48.740 --> 00:28:50.800
like how do you decide
that when you sit

00:28:50.800 --> 00:28:52.630
down to write something that's
it's going to be intended

00:28:52.630 --> 00:28:55.250
for children versus for adults.

00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:58.050
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: So the
difference between YA and adult

00:28:58.050 --> 00:29:02.830
that I can see is that
adult is more reflective.

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:04.430
It's like looking back often.

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:05.730
You know what I mean?

00:29:05.730 --> 00:29:07.510
It's like -- Okay,
so I put it this way.

00:29:07.510 --> 00:29:10.660
So young people have this
amount of experience.

00:29:10.660 --> 00:29:13.130
Right? At 16, you
have this much.

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:15.760
As an adult, you know,
that starts to widen.

00:29:15.760 --> 00:29:17.750
And by the time you
get ancient like me,

00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:23.150
it's like I got so
much experience.

00:29:23.150 --> 00:29:24.490
But it's a reflective thing.

00:29:24.490 --> 00:29:25.790
So it's like looking back.

00:29:25.790 --> 00:29:29.820
So I can judge today by
this many yesterdays.

00:29:29.820 --> 00:29:32.510
Young people can judge today
by this many yesterdays.

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:35.340
So writing for young people
is more about discovery,

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:39.530
learning who you are, figuring
out where you want to go.

00:29:39.530 --> 00:29:44.240
Writing for adults is
more like regret, I guess.

00:29:46.410 --> 00:29:48.030
I really should've
gotten together

00:29:48.030 --> 00:29:50.050
with that guy instead
of that guy.

00:29:50.050 --> 00:29:52.250
You know what I mean?

00:29:52.250 --> 00:29:53.720
So I think that's
the difference.

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:55.800
And also there's a
pacing difference.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:29:57.580
So if you want to
write for young people,

00:29:57.580 --> 00:29:59.550
it's a different kind of pacing.

00:29:59.550 --> 00:30:01.730
It has to be a little faster.

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:06.600
The plot needs to be
less heavy, I guess.

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:07.900
I don't know.

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:10.180
There's a lot of different
things but it's really

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:12.740
about discovery versus
reflection.

00:30:12.740 --> 00:30:14.040
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:19.060
&gt;&gt; Hi. So you talked about
how in your first few books,

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:21.880
your verse was more
simplistic and you wanted

00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:24.570
to catch younger readers and
now you've moved into prose

00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:26.990
and you're writing a
book almost all in prose.

00:30:26.990 --> 00:30:30.470
Do you find the two, verse and
prose, very different to write

00:30:30.470 --> 00:30:33.090
or do you them similar?

00:30:33.090 --> 00:30:35.080
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: I actually
prefer writing in verse.

00:30:35.080 --> 00:30:38.370
Verse is, it's every word
has count has the page.

00:30:38.370 --> 00:30:40.260
There's a lot of -- It's
a lot more difficult

00:30:40.260 --> 00:30:41.560
to write in verse.

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:42.970
I will tell you that for a
fact because you have to --

00:30:42.970 --> 00:30:44.360
Every single word has to count.

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:45.830
So it's word choice.

00:30:45.830 --> 00:30:51.420
It's deciding what can, what
one word can take the place

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:54.190
of like a whole sentence,
maybe, sometimes.

00:30:54.190 --> 00:30:59.310
So I'm going to actually --
I'm going to write in verse.

00:30:59.310 --> 00:31:04.080
I'm going to do a middle grade
novel because this one child

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:06.030
of ours, the one that
just started high school,

00:31:06.030 --> 00:31:08.400
he came to us with
PTSD, like because

00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:12.360
of early childhood trauma from
like the boyfriends and stuff.

00:31:12.360 --> 00:31:13.780
So when he first got to us,

00:31:13.780 --> 00:31:17.890
he would like have daily throw
himself on the floor meltdowns,

00:31:17.890 --> 00:31:19.840
screaming into his hoodie.

00:31:19.840 --> 00:31:22.440
So he'd go to school and
when he started school

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:26.490
in this new school, everybody
thought he was the freak

00:31:26.490 --> 00:31:28.060
but nobody wanted to know why.

00:31:28.060 --> 00:31:29.360
You know what I mean?

00:31:29.360 --> 00:31:32.640
So I want to write a
book for kids like him,

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:35.070
for the classmates
of kids like him

00:31:35.070 --> 00:31:38.500
so they can understand there's
a reason why kids might be

00:31:38.500 --> 00:31:39.800
in that kind of space.

00:31:39.800 --> 00:31:41.100
And I will tell you,
those things used

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:43.290
to happen three or
four times a day.

00:31:43.290 --> 00:31:46.180
They don't happen at
all anymore, seriously.

00:31:46.180 --> 00:31:49.190
I mean, and it was a slow
change, like a slow change.

00:31:49.190 --> 00:31:50.750
And like last year,
I would say it would

00:31:50.750 --> 00:31:52.440
like once every couple weeks.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:55.160
This year, like it's done.

00:31:55.160 --> 00:31:57.440
So they can come around.

00:31:57.440 --> 00:31:58.740
They can change.

00:31:58.740 --> 00:32:02.550
And they should be allowed
to change and to have friends

00:32:02.550 --> 00:32:05.430
that accept them but I think
verse is going to be the way

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:09.170
to tell that story because it's,
again, such an interior story.

00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:10.990
So verse is like, it's

00:32:10.990 --> 00:32:13.200
like really viewing
this world, right.

00:32:13.200 --> 00:32:15.670
Prose is like describing
the world.

00:32:15.670 --> 00:32:17.950
This is like viewing the world.

00:32:17.950 --> 00:32:19.250
And, you know, there are a lot

00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:22.010
of giant successful
verse novels out now.

00:32:22.010 --> 00:32:24.660
Jason Reynolds books, you know,
Jacqueline Woodson's books,

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:26.310
those great making rhymes.

00:32:26.310 --> 00:32:29.480
Those books are like
great, great in verse books.

00:32:29.480 --> 00:32:31.070
So I'm going to go back
to it for that book

00:32:31.070 --> 00:32:32.560
and then we'll see
because, you know,

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:35.580
I do want to have a wider
audience and there are kids

00:32:35.580 --> 00:32:36.880
like they look at verse

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:38.180
and they're like,
unh-uh, not for me.

00:32:38.180 --> 00:32:41.140
Right? So I want both
because I'm hopeful

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:43.320
that my writing will
attract both eventually

00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:45.470
and like the prose
lovers will go to verse

00:32:45.470 --> 00:32:47.690
and the verse lovers
will go to prose.

00:32:47.690 --> 00:32:53.510
And then everybody can love me.

00:32:53.510 --> 00:32:55.030
I think -- Are we done?

00:32:55.030 --> 00:32:56.670
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:32:56.670 --> 00:32:57.970
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: Three minutes.

00:32:57.970 --> 00:33:00.830
I got time.

00:33:00.830 --> 00:33:05.080
&gt;&gt; So how or why did you
decide to make a book or series

00:33:05.080 --> 00:33:08.750
out of your family story instead
of just keeping it private?

00:33:08.750 --> 00:33:12.100
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: So why did I
choose to write "Crank" instead

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:16.510
of just keeping it
as a private story?

00:33:16.510 --> 00:33:19.030
Because my daughter was the kid

00:33:19.030 --> 00:33:23.800
that we just expected
her to be like somebody.

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:25.100
You know what I mean?

00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:26.400
I mean, she has talent.

00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:28.190
She was a straight
A plus student.

00:33:28.190 --> 00:33:30.510
She has 150 IQ, like
brilliant kid.

00:33:30.510 --> 00:33:35.000
And then you made
one wrong choice.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.650
You know, she chose to go
with this guy and to get high

00:33:37.650 --> 00:33:43.020
and her entire, all her dreams
dissolved with that one choice.

00:33:43.020 --> 00:33:46.340
I needed to write that book --
Well, first I needed to write it

00:33:46.340 --> 00:33:49.610
for me to figure out why.

00:33:49.610 --> 00:33:52.620
But then I needed to write it
for teens because I wanted --

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:57.290
I knew if I could just turn
one kid or two kids away

00:33:57.290 --> 00:34:00.830
from that choice, it would mean
something really special to me.

00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:04.890
And now it's been, I'm
serious, tens of thousands

00:34:04.890 --> 00:34:08.180
of young people that I've
gotten messages from and emails

00:34:08.180 --> 00:34:12.020
from and, you know, and they
tweet me and they Instagram me

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:15.230
and whatever and that I've
been able to make that kind

00:34:15.230 --> 00:34:20.750
of difference in somebody else's
life made it all worthwhile.

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:24.510
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:34:24.510 --> 00:34:28.280
[ Applause ]

00:34:28.280 --> 00:34:29.580
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: Thank you.

00:34:29.580 --> 00:34:33.060
Alright, well okay, so
then I guess I'm done here

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:38.680
because they're like -- Is there
one more question somewhere?

00:34:38.680 --> 00:34:41.180
Yeah.

00:34:41.180 --> 00:34:43.640
&gt;&gt; Hi. I just wanted to
give the kids a chance first

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:45.340
because I've been reading
your books since I was

00:34:45.340 --> 00:34:46.940
in middle school and I'm
a master student now.

00:34:46.940 --> 00:34:49.710
So you're like, whew, you're
like part of my childhood

00:34:49.710 --> 00:34:52.970
and seeing you in the flesh
just I'm nervous and everything.

00:34:52.970 --> 00:34:56.940
I have had a question
since I was a child,

00:34:56.940 --> 00:34:58.700
since I started reading
your books

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:01.000
of how the heck do
you deal with it?

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:06.350
How do you deal with writing of
such difficult heavy subjects

00:35:06.350 --> 00:35:09.570
and you as a human being, you've
been doing this for decades now,

00:35:09.570 --> 00:35:15.200
like how do you cope with
so much pain and make it

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:18.780
so beautiful and easy to
understand and easy to connect

00:35:18.780 --> 00:35:22.180
with for anyone that
reads your books?

00:35:22.180 --> 00:35:24.700
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: Again, I think
it's just a matter of being able

00:35:24.700 --> 00:35:29.580
to take some of that on myself
for so many other people,

00:35:29.580 --> 00:35:32.660
that I actually feel
I have a relationship

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:33.960
with the creator and, you know,

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:37.080
I think I was put
here to do what I do.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:40.040
And so, He gives it back.

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:41.340
Do you know what I mean?

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:44.630
So my life, I've been so blessed
in so many ways that I feel

00:35:44.630 --> 00:35:47.150
like if I can bless
some other lives

00:35:47.150 --> 00:35:49.950
that I'm doing what
I was put here to do.

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:51.390
&gt;&gt; I agree with that.

00:35:51.390 --> 00:35:52.760
Thank you so much
for everything.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:54.060
&gt;&gt; Ellen Hopkins: Thank you.

00:35:54.060 --> 00:35:55.360
Okay, I'm wrapping it up.

00:35:55.360 --> 00:35:58.340
I got the sign here, wrap it up.

00:35:58.340 --> 00:35:59.640
So you guys come.

00:35:59.640 --> 00:36:02.650
I'll sign some books for you
downstairs at 4:00 o'clock.

00:36:02.650 --> 00:36:03.950
Catch me in the hallway
if you want.

00:36:03.950 --> 00:36:05.250
I'm not going anywhere.

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:08.230
If you got other questions, I'll
be here and just thank you guys

00:36:08.230 --> 00:36:10.140
for being with me
on this journey.

00:36:10.140 --> 00:36:11.440
I love you [applause].

